.SH "NAME"
crowbar \- Build and manage third\-party software
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.sp
.nf
\fIcrowbar\fR [\-\-working\-dir <dir>] <command> [<options>] [<arguments>]
.fi
.sp
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
\fBcrowbar\fR is a CLI tool for building packages defined by \fBcrowbar\&.txtpb\fR files\&. It is built on top of LUCI\(cqs \fBcipkg\fR to leverage its reproducibility and caching mechanisms\&.
.sp
By default, \fBcrowbar\fR operates within the Git repository containing the current working directory\&.
.SH "GLOBAL OPTIONS"
.PP
\-\-working\-dir <dir>
.RS 4
Overrides current working directory to <dir>\&.
.RE
.SH "COMMANDS"
.PP
build
.RS 4
\fBcrowbar build\fR
[\-\-overwrite] <package>\&...
.sp
Builds the specified packages\&.
.PP
The \fBpackage\fR Argument
.RS 4
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Paths starting with
\fB\&.\fR
are resolved from the working directory\&.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Paths not starting with
\fB\&.\fR
are resolved from Git repository\(cqs root\&.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Each path must point to a directory that contains a
\fBcrowbar\&.txtpb\fR
file\&.
.RE
.RE
.PP
Options
.RS 4
.PP
\-\-overwrite
.RS 4
Write the build result to the local Git checkout\&.
.RE
.RE
.RE
.PP
fmt
.RS 4
\fBcrowbar fmt\fR
.sp
Formats all
\fBcrowbar\&.txtpb\fR
files found under the current working directory\&.
.RE
.SH "CROWBAR\&.TXTPB CONFIGURATION"
.sp
Each package typically contains:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "  1." 4.2
.\}
"upstream" description, which typically are HTTP URLs (e\&.g\&. zip files or tarballs) or Git commit references\&.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "  2." 4.2
.\}
"Input" describing steps to transform upstream into code or build artifacts\&. Typical actions include "unpack" and "patch"\&.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 3.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.sp -1
.IP "  3." 4.2
.\}
"Output" describing where the result should be stored (e\&.g\&. inside the Git checkout for vendoring code, or to be published to CIPD)\&.
.RE
.sp
Example of a typical third\-party dependency distributed as a ZIP archive that does not require local patches:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
upstream {
  artifacts {
    name: "foo\-1\&.0\&.zip"
    http: {
      url: "https://example\&.com/foo\-1\&.0\&.zip"
      digest: "sha256:abcdef\&.\&.\&."
    }
  }
}
stages {
  input {
    unpack { default {} }
  }
  output {
    update { git {} }
  }
}
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
.sp
.SH "COMMON USAGE"
.sp
To build a package in a local directory and update the checkout with the result:
.sp
.if n \{\
.RS 4
.\}
.nf
crowbar build \&./path/to/package \-\-overwrite
.fi
.if n \{\
.RE
.\}
